         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ Will you be so kind, dear Professor Greene, as to publish, in some one of the botanical periodicals of your country, the fact that the  ¶ Jusssiaea repens  ¶ of American phytographers is not the Li...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">92.12.05b</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Edward Greene</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from 'On <name key="Jussiaea%20repens">Jussiaea repens</name> of Linnaeus', </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Erythea, </seg>
                     <seg style="">vol. 1, p. 61 (B93.03.06).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Will you be so kind, dear Professor Greene, as to publish, in some one of the botanical periodicals of your country, the fact that the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Jusssiaea repens </seg>of American phytographers is not the Linnaean plant that was so named; for that has the petals white, except their base (just as in <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Ranunculus%20aquatilis">Ranunculus aquatilis</name>
               </seg>) as was stated long ago by Rheede and by Ray, in their definitions of what afterward became the type of Linnaeus' species.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The genuine <seg style="font-style: italic; ">J. repens</seg> is known with certainty only from continental India, where the smaller species, with petals always entirely yellow, does not exist; but which, however, must approach very near to the Indian confines. This is the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">J. diffusa</seg> of Forskaal; and, as Mr. Oliver has shown, it is also the African plant,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Oliver (1868-77), vol. 2, p. 488.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> and the same occurs throughout Australia. I believe it is also the American plant. Mr. Mohr, of Alabama, who, at my suggestion made through Mr. Thomas Meehan, investigated the case, reports that in the Southern United States the plant called <seg style="font-style: italic; ">J. repens</seg> has always quite yellow petals.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As the subject is one of some interest from the point of geographical distribution, will you kindly make known at an early date your own experience in connection with the American <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Jussiaea</seg>, and address a note on the subject, to Professor Leveillè.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully yours,</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>F<seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">erd. von Mueller.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Melbourne, Australia, 5 Dec, 1892.</seg>
               <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Greene comments on the letter (p. 62) that 'I had from him nearly two years ago, an intimation that our American </seg>
                        <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Jussicaea</seg>
                        <seg style=""> was not </seg>
                        <seg style="font-style: italic; ">J. repens</seg>
                        <seg style="">; and in Flora Franciscana (page 227), I acceded to his proposition that we have in North America only the </seg>
                        <seg style="font-style: italic; ">J. diffusa</seg>
                        <seg style="">'. However, Greene also pointed out that he had treated </seg>
                        <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Jussiaea</seg>
                        <seg style=""> as indistinguishable from </seg>
                        <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Ludwigia</seg>
                        <seg style="">, under which name he reported the analysis; see Greene (1891-97), part 1, p. 227, issued 1891.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <name key="Jussiaea%20diffusa">Jussiaea diffusa</name>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Jussiaea%20repens">Jussiaea repens</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Ranunculus%20aquatilis">Ranunculus aquatilis</name>
            </p>
         </div>
